For even "N", notice that the Nyquist component formula_93 is handled specially.

This interpolation is "not unique": aliasing implies that one could add "N" to any of the complex-sinusoid frequencies (e.g. changing formula_94 to formula_95) without changing the interpolation property, but giving "different" values in between the formula_34 points. The choice above, however, is typical because it has two useful properties. First, it consists of sinusoids whose frequencies have the smallest possible magnitudes: the interpolation is bandlimited. Second, if the formula_34 are real numbers, then formula_98 is real as well.

In contrast, the most obvious trigonometric interpolation polynomial is the one in which the frequencies range from 0 to formula_99 (instead of roughly formula_100 to formula_101 as above), similar to the inverse DFT formula. This interpolation does "not" minimize the slope, and is "not" generally real-valued for real formula_34; its use is a common mistake.

